  "output": "This is a Python job-scraper (no React/frontend exists), so I've mapped your ask onto what's actually here: SQLite access patterns, HTTP fetch behavior, and the filter/dedup pipeline. 114 sources are configured, several documented as \"thousands of roles\" (Amazon, Microsoft, Netflix), so batch-scale issues matter here.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (the big one)\n\n`store.py:55-74` issues one `SELECT` per job, then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` per job, inside a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    ...\n```\n\nWith 114 sources and boards like Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix returning hundreds-to-thousands of jobs each, this is thousands of round-trips per run. Fix: pull all existing hashes for the batch in one query, diff in memory, then use `executemany` for writes:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's 999-var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(self.conn.execute(q, chunk).fetchall())\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,:source,...)\"\"\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        self.conn.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                               [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/900 + 3) statements.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job\n\n`filters.py:15-27`: `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job loop** driven by `filter_jobs`'s list comprehension (`filters.py:49`). For every job fetched, the same include/exclude keyword list is re-compiled into regex patterns from scratch.\n\n```python\n# filters.py — current: recompiled N times (once per job)\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFix — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=(), exclude=(), locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\nWith thousands of jobs across 114 sources, this is thousands of redundant `re.compile` calls saved per run.\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` / `key` recomputed per job\n\n`Job.content_hash` (`models.py:66`) and `Job.key` (`models.py:55`) are `@property`s that recompute a SHA-256 hash / f-string on every access. In `store.py`, each job hits `.content_hash` once in `diff()` and again inside `_insert`/`_update` via `to_row()` — 2x hashing per job, and `.key` is computed 3+ times (lookup, `to_row()`, `WHERE key=?`). Cheap individually, but pure waste at thousands-of-jobs scale. Fix: compute once per job and reuse:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    key, chash = job.key, job.content_hash\n    row = existing.get(key)\n    ...\n```\n(This falls out naturally from the batched rewrite in #1 since `to_row()` would only be called once per job either way.)\n\n## 4. Caching opportunity — no conditional HTTP requests\n\n`fetchers.py` fetches full payloads from every board every run (every 12h per the cron schedule) with no `ETag`/`If-Modified-Since` support, even though `_request` (`fetchers.py:31`) already centralizes all HTTP calls — a natural place to add it. Greenhouse, Lever, and Ashby all support conditional GETs. For boards that haven't changed, you're paying full download + full parse + full `Store.diff` scan for nothing.\n\n```python\nasync def _get_json(client, url, *, etag_cache: dict | None = None, cache_key=None, **kw):\n    headers = kw.pop(\"headers\", {})\n    if etag_cache is not None and cache_key in etag_cache:\n        headers[\"If-None-Match\"] = etag_cache[cache_key]\n    r = await _request(client, url, headers=headers, **kw)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return None  # caller keeps previous result / skips\n    if etag_cache is not None and \"etag\" in r.headers:\n        etag_cache[cache_key] = r.headers[\"etag\"]\n    return r.json()\n```\nWould need the ETag persisted between runs (e.g. a new `meta` row per source, using the existing `Store.get_meta`/`set_meta` you already built for the scan marker).\n\n## 5. Unnecessary work — sequential, blocking notifier dispatch\n\n`notify.py:105-109` runs `notify_console → notify_slack → notify_webhook → notify_email → notify_sms` strictly sequentially, and several are blocking network calls (`httpx.post` synchronous, `smtplib.SMTP`). None depend on each other. Called from inside `async def run()` (`pipeline.py:44`), so it also blocks the event loop, though with only one coroutine running that's mostly academic here. If notification latency ever matters (SMS/webhook fan-out), thread-pool them:\n\n```python\nfrom concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor\n\ndef dispatch(new: list[Job], changed: list[Job]) -> None:\n    def run(fn):\n        try:\n            fn(new, changed)\n        except Exception as e:\n            print(f\"  ! notifier {fn.__name__} failed: {e}\")\n    with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=len(NOTIFIERS)) as pool:\n        list(pool.map(run, NOTIFIERS))\n```\nLow priority — only worth it if a slow SMTP server is currently delaying the whole run.\n\n## 6. Memory — no leak (short-lived process), but avoidable peak usage\n\nThis is a cron-invoked script (`.github/workflows/scrape.yaml`, every 12h) that exits after each run, so there's no long-lived-process leak to chase. The one real waste: every `Job` carries `raw=j` (`fetchers.py`, e.g. line 72, 92, 121...) — the **entire unparsed source payload** — for every fetched job, even ones later dropped by `filter_jobs`. `to_row()` (`models.py:71-75`) discards `raw` before it ever reaches SQLite, and nothing else reads it. For Amazon/Microsoft with `max_pages=40` (400 jobs) each holding a full API record, across 114 sources fetched with `concurrency=8` in flight simultaneously, that's meaningfully more peak memory than needed for objects that get filtered out and thrown away. If `raw` isn't used for debugging today, drop it at parse time; if it is useful for debugging, only keep it behind a debug flag.\n\n## Priority order\n1. **#1 (N+1 diff)** — biggest win, straightforward fix, directly proportional to your growing source count.\n2. **#2 (regex recompilation)** — trivial fix, real savings at current job volumes.\n3. **#4 (conditional HTTP)** — biggest win for *fetch* time/bandwidth if boards rarely change, but requires new state tracking — worth it only if run time/rate-limit pressure is actually a pain point.\n4. **#3, #5, #6** — minor, do opportunistically.\n\nWant me to implement #1 and #2 now? They're the two with the clearest ROI and no design tradeoffs.\n",
